    lifeStory: [
      "Agrippa I was raised partly in Rome among the imperial family and used those connections skillfully, eventually being granted kingship over a territory that, by AD 41, matched the full extent of his grandfather Herod the Great's old kingdom — a remarkable political comeback for a man who had earlier been imprisoned for debt and disloyalty accusations.",
      "Acts 12 describes Agrippa moving against the young Jerusalem church: he had James, the brother of John, put to death with the sword, and when he saw this pleased the Jewish leadership, he had Peter arrested too, intending to bring him out for public trial after Passover. Peter was miraculously freed from prison by an angel the night before his planned execution (Acts 12:1-11).",
      "Acts then records Agrippa's death in vivid terms: appearing before the people of Tyre and Sidon in royal robes, he gave a speech, and the crowd shouted that this was the voice of a god, not a man. 'Immediately an angel of the Lord struck him down, because he did not give God the glory, and he was eaten by worms and breathed his last' (Acts 12:20-23).",
    ],
