      "Stephen's role quickly expanded beyond administration. Acts describes him as full of grace and power, performing great wonders and signs among the people. This provoked opposition from members of a synagogue of Hellenistic Jews, who argued with him but, unable to withstand \"the wisdom and the Spirit by which he spoke,\" resorted to producing false witnesses who accused him of speaking blasphemy against Moses, the temple, and God, and had him dragged before the Sanhedrin (Acts 6:8-15). Even his accusers noticed his face looked \"like the face of an angel\" as he stood before the council.",
      "Given the chance to answer the charges, Stephen delivered the longest speech in Acts — a sweeping retelling of Israelite history from Abraham through Joseph, Moses, and the wilderness tabernacle to Solomon's temple, arguing that God had never been confined to a building made by hands and that Israel's history was marked by repeated resistance to God's messengers. He turned the accusation back on the council, calling them \"stiff-necked\" people who, like their ancestors who killed the prophets, had now betrayed and murdered the Righteous One (Acts 7:1-53). Enraged, the council members ground their teeth at him — but Stephen, gazing into heaven, said he saw the glory of God and Jesus standing at God's right hand, a claim that pushed the crowd over the edge (Acts 7:54-56).",
      "They dragged him out of the city and stoned him. As he died, Stephen echoed Jesus's own words from the cross, crying out, \"Lord Jesus, receive my spirit,\" and \"Lord, do not hold this sin against them,\" before he died (Acts 7:57-60). Acts notes that the witnesses laid their coats at the feet of a young man named Saul, who approved of his killing (Acts 7:58; 8:1) — the same Saul who would later become the apostle Paul after his own dramatic encounter with Christ on the road to Damascus. Stephen's death also triggered a wider persecution that scattered believers from Jerusalem, which Acts presents as the catalyst that spread the Christian message beyond the city (Acts 8:1-4).",
