    role: "The first human being, formed by God from the dust of the ground",
    summary: "The first man, created directly by God and placed in the Garden of Eden — his disobedience in eating the forbidden fruit is treated throughout Scripture as the origin point of human sin and mortality, and the New Testament repeatedly casts Christ as the 'second Adam' who reverses his failure.",
    lifeStory: [
      "According to Genesis 1:26-27 and 2:7, God formed Adam from the dust of the ground and breathed into his nostrils the breath of life, making him a living being made in the divine image. He was given dominion over the fish, birds, and every living creature, and set apart from the rest of creation as its steward.",
      "God placed Adam in the Garden of Eden 'to work it and keep it' (Genesis 2:15), permitting him to eat freely from every tree except the tree of the knowledge of good and evil, under penalty of death (Genesis 2:16-17). Adam was given the task of naming every animal God brought before him, though none was found to be a suitable companion (Genesis 2:19-20).",
      "Seeing that 'it is not good that the man should be alone,' God caused a deep sleep to fall on Adam and formed a woman from one of his ribs. On seeing her, Adam declared, 'This at last is bone of my bones and flesh of my flesh,' and the narrative notes the two were naked and unashamed (Genesis 2:18, 21-25).",
      "A serpent deceived Eve into eating fruit from the forbidden tree, and she gave some to Adam, who ate as well. Their eyes were opened, they realized their nakedness, and they hid from God's presence — the event traditionally called the Fall (Genesis 3:1-8).",
      "God confronted Adam, who blamed Eve ('the woman whom you gave to be with me'), and pronounced a series of curses: the ground would be cursed, yielding thorns and thistles, and Adam would eat bread by the sweat of his face until his return to the dust from which he was taken. Adam and Eve were then expelled from Eden and barred from the tree of life by cherubim with a flaming sword (Genesis 3:9-24).",
      "Outside Eden, Adam 'knew' Eve, who bore Cain and then Abel; after Cain murdered Abel, Eve bore a third son, Seth, whom Genesis credits as the line through which humanity continued (Genesis 4:1-2, 25).",
      "Genesis 5 records Adam's genealogy: he had other sons and daughters, lived a total of 930 years, and died — the first death by natural cause recorded after the Fall (Genesis 5:3-5).",
      "The New Testament repeatedly uses Adam as a theological reference point. Luke's genealogy traces Jesus's ancestry all the way back to 'Adam, the son of God' (Luke 3:38). Paul contrasts Adam and Christ as two representative heads of humanity — sin and death entering the world through Adam's one act of disobedience, and grace and life coming through Christ (Romans 5:12-19; 1 Corinthians 15:22, 45-49). Paul also cites the order of Adam's and Eve's creation in his instructions to Timothy (1 Timothy 2:13-14), and Jude quotes a prophecy attributed to 'Enoch, the seventh from Adam' (Jude 1:14), reflecting Adam's role as the fixed starting point of the biblical timeline.",
    ],
    occupation: "Cultivator and keeper of the Garden of Eden; afterward a tiller of the cursed ground",
    placesLived: "The Garden of Eden, then unspecified lands 'east of Eden'",
