    id: "deborah",
    name: "Deborah",
    pronunciation: "DEB-uh-ruh",
    tier: "significant",
    role: "Judge and prophetess of Israel; military strategist in the defeat of the Canaanite general Sisera",
    summary: "The only woman named as a judge of Israel in the book of Judges — a prophetess who summoned and accompanied the commander Barak into battle against a Canaanite coalition, and whose victory hymn in Judges 5 is among the oldest surviving pieces of Hebrew poetry.",
    lifeStory: [
      "Deborah is introduced as \"a prophetess, the wife of Lapidoth,\" who judged Israel while sitting under a palm tree between Ramah and Bethel in the hill country of Ephraim, where Israelites came to her for legal decisions (Judges 4:4-5). This was during the 20-year oppression of Israel by Jabin, a Canaanite king of Hazor, whose army commander Sisera controlled 900 iron chariots.",
      "Deborah summoned Barak of Naphtali and relayed a divine command that he muster 10,000 men to Mount Tabor to confront Sisera. Barak agreed only on condition that Deborah accompany him; she consented but told him the campaign's honor would instead go to a woman, since \"the LORD shall sell Sisera into the hand of a woman\" (Judges 4:6-9).",
      "In the ensuing battle, Israel routed Sisera's forces; Sisera himself fled on foot to the tent of Jael, wife of Heber the Kenite, who gave him refuge, then killed him by driving a tent peg through his temple as he slept — fulfilling Deborah's prophecy (Judges 4:10-22).",
      "Judges 5 preserves the victory hymn known as the Song of Deborah, sung by Deborah and Barak together, celebrating the battle and Jael's act; many scholars consider its archaic Hebrew grammar and vocabulary evidence that it is among the oldest texts preserved in the Hebrew Bible, likely composed close to the events it describes.",
    ],
    occupation: "Judge, prophetess, and military strategist",
    placesLived: "The hill country of Ephraim, between Ramah and Bethel",
    noExtraBiblicalRecordNote: "No archaeological find or non-biblical text names Deborah. Scholars do treat the archaic linguistic features of the Song of Deborah (Judges 5) as internal literary-critical evidence for the poem's antiquity, but this is a textual/linguistic observation, not independent extrabiblical corroboration.",
    verses: [
      { reference: "Judges 4", note: "Summons Barak; prophesies Sisera's death at a woman's hand" },
      { reference: "Judges 5", note: "The Song of Deborah, a victory hymn considered among the oldest texts in the Hebrew Bible" },
    ],
    sources: [
      { label: "Encyclopaedia Britannica: Deborah", url: "https://www.britannica.com/biography/Deborah-Old-Testament-figure" },
    ],
