    id: "ezra",
    name: "Ezra",
    pronunciation: "EZ-ruh",
    tier: "significant",
    role: "Priest and scribe; leader of a return from Babylonian exile",
    summary: "A priest and scribe 'skilled in the Law of Moses' who led a group of exiles back to Jerusalem from Babylon, reformed the community's adherence to the Law, and worked alongside Nehemiah to publicly read and renew commitment to the Torah.",
    lifeStory: [
      "Ezra is introduced as a priest descended from Aaron through a long genealogical line, and as 'a scribe skilled in the Law of Moses that the Lord, the God of Israel, had given,' whose hand 'was on him' because he had 'set his heart to study the Law of the Lord, and to do it and to teach his statutes and rules in Israel' (Ezra 7:1-10). In the seventh year of King Artaxerxes, he obtained a royal letter granting him authority to lead a group of exiles back to Jerusalem, along with silver and gold for the temple and authority to appoint judges and teachers (Ezra 7:11-26).",
      "Ezra organized the returning group at the Ahava Canal, and rather than requesting a military escort from the king — having told him that God's hand was on those who sought him — proclaimed a fast so the group would arrive safely by prayer rather than armed protection, a decision he says he was ashamed to reverse after making that declaration to the king (Ezra 8:21-23).",
      "Upon arriving in Jerusalem, Ezra was confronted with the news that many of the people, including priests and Levites, had intermarried with surrounding peoples in violation of the Law — a practice that risked religious assimilation and idolatry. Ezra tore his garments, pulled hair from his head and beard in distress, and prayed a public confession on behalf of the community, leading to a covenant to separate from these marriages (Ezra 9-10).",
      "In the book of Nehemiah, Ezra reappears as the central figure of a major public reading of the Law: he stood on a wooden platform before the assembled people at the Water Gate and read from the Law from early morning until midday, with Levites moving through the crowd to help the people understand it, resulting in a day of national weeping, followed by a joyful covenant-renewal festival (Nehemiah 8). He and Nehemiah are shown working the same era and cause, though the biblical text does not clearly specify how much time separated Ezra's own arrival from Nehemiah's.",
      "Jewish tradition credits Ezra with a formative role in shaping post-exilic Judaism — including, in later rabbinic tradition, organizing the canon of Scripture and reintroducing the practice of public Torah reading — though these traditions extend well beyond what the biblical text itself directly states about him.",
    ],
    occupation: "Priest and scribe",
    placesLived: "Babylon (before his return); Jerusalem, after leading a group of exiles back",
    noExtraBiblicalRecordNote: "No extra-biblical inscription or document names Ezra specifically. The broader historical context of his mission — the Persian practice of sponsoring the return and religious reestablishment of subject peoples, reflected in policy on the Cyrus Cylinder a century earlier, and the administrative structure of the Persian province of Yehud (Judah) attested in seal impressions and coins bearing the name 'Yehud' from this general period — provides plausible background support for the setting the book describes, without confirming Ezra himself.",
